quick_wins.title: World-writable files detected (34761 files)
quick_wins.recommendation: URGENT: Remove world-write permissions from critical system files immediately. Review web content permissions - consider using group ownership instead of world-writable. Use 'chmod o-w <filename>' to remove world-write permissions. Consider using ACLs (setfacl) for fine-grained access control where needed

quick_wins.title: Web directory permission issues detected
quick_wins.recommendation: Set web directories to 755 (rwxr-xr-x) and web files to 644 (rw-r--r--). Use proper web server user/group ownership. Consider using a separate user for web content.

quick_wins.title: Suspicious SUID/SGID binaries detected
quick_wins.recommendation: Review each suspicious binary. Remove SUID/SGID bits if not needed: 'chmod u-s <file>' or 'chmod g-s <file>'. Ensure suspicious binaries are from trusted sources and properly maintained.

quick_wins.title: Log file permission issues (19 files)
quick_wins.recommendation: Set log files to mode 640 (rw-r-----) or 644 (rw-r--r--) and ensure proper ownership. Use logrotate with proper permissions.

quick_wins.title: Configuration file permission issues (26 files)
quick_wins.recommendation: Set configuration files to mode 644 (rw-r--r--) for general configs, 640 (rw-r-----) for sensitive configs, and ensure root ownership. Use 'chown root:root <config_file> && chmod 644 <config_file>'

quick_wins.title: Insecure SSH setting: permitrootlogin
quick_wins.recommendation: Set 'PermitRootLogin no' in /etc/ssh/sshd_config

quick_wins.title: Insecure SSH setting: passwordauthentication
quick_wins.recommendation: Set 'PasswordAuthentication no' and use key-based authentication

quick_wins.title: Insecure SSH setting: protocol
quick_wins.recommendation: Set 'Protocol 2' in /etc/ssh/sshd_config

quick_wins.title: SSH running on default port
quick_wins.recommendation: Consider changing SSH port to a non-standard port for security through obscurity

quick_wins.recommendation: Ensure OS is supported and receiving security updates

quick_wins.recommendation: Keep kernel updated to latest version for security patches

appendices.methodology:
VigileGuard Security Audit Methodology:
        
        1. System Discovery: Automated identification of system components, services, and configurations
        2. Configuration Analysis: Review of security-relevant configuration files and settings  
        3. Permission Assessment: Analysis of file, directory, and service permissions
        4. Network Security Review: Evaluation of network services, firewall rules, and exposed ports
        5. Web Server Security: Assessment of web server configurations and SSL/TLS settings
        6. Compliance Mapping: Alignment of findings with industry security frameworks
        7. Risk Assessment: Severity scoring based on potential impact and exploitability
        8. Remediation Guidance: Actionable recommendations for issue resolution
        
        The audit covers multiple security domains including access controls, network security,
        web server configurations, and system hardening. All checks are performed using read-only
        operations where possible to minimize impact on production systems.
